Refer to this document when the execution stack breaks and you lose track of
where you are in the memory initialization sequence.


1. Environment & Bootstrapping: Escaping the BIOS
        We use the Limine bootloader (modern open-source bootloader designed mainly for hobby OS development) to handle the ugly firmware initialization.
        Limine forces the CPU into 64-bit Long Mode, establishes a flat stack, and jumps directly into our C entry point (`kernel_main`).

2. Hardware Tables (GDT & IDT): Taking Control of the CPU
        Before we can trust the CPU to run complex logic, we must configure its core
        execution tables manually.
        • GDT (Global Descriptor Table): Defines flat 64-bit code and data segments.
        • IDT (Interrupt Descriptor Table): Maps hardware events and CPU exceptions
          (e.g., Divide-by-Zero, Page Faults) to specific C handlers. If this is broken,
          the hardware triple-faults and reboots instantly.

3. Memory Management (PMM & VMM): The Foundation
        Memory abstraction is the absolute core of this project. It is built in three
        distinct, non-negotiable layers:
        • PMM (Physical Memory Manager): A primitive page bitmap allocator tracking
          which 4KB blocks of raw RAM are physically occupied.
        • VMM (Virtual Memory Manager): C logic manipulating x86_64 4-level page tables
          (PML4, PDPT, PD, PT) to map arbitrary virtual spaces.
        • Heap Allocator: Implementation of `kmalloc()` and `kfree()` to allow the
          kernel to handle dynamic data structures.

4. Interrupts & Multitasking: The Research Phase
        We transition the system from a single execution thread into a true concurrent
        kernel.
        • Timer: Configure the APIC (Advanced Programmable Interrupt Controller)
          timer to yield execution every few milliseconds.
        • Context Switch: Hardcore Assembly routines to push current CPU registers
          onto the stack, swap stack pointers, and pop the state of the next task.
        • Scheduling: Implementation of a custom scheduling algorithm. No generic
          Round-Robin; code a lean scheduler optimized for bare-metal execution.
 (im planning to design a new scheduling algo lol!)

5. The User Space Transition: Dropping to Ring 3
        Running user applications inside the kernel (Ring 0) is garbage design. A single
        application bug will crash the entire machine.
        • TSS (Task State Segment): Hardwired CPU structure required to hold the
          kernel stack pointer during privilege shifts.
        • Privilege Drop: Use the `STAR`/`LSTAR` MSRs and the `sysret` instruction
          to safely drop the CPU's privilege level into Ring 3.
        • Syscalls: Implement an explicit `syscall` handler interface so untrusted
          Ring 3 binaries can safely request execution services from the kernel.


6.The VFS & ELF Loader: Running Real Programs.
        To run arbitrary user binaries, the system must abstract storage and understand
        standard executable layouts.
        • VFS (Virtual File System): A unified abstraction layer over raw storage.
          Backed by a clean TarFS or basic ext2 read-only implementation.
        • ELF Parser: Reads compiled ELF64 binaries from disk, parses program headers,
          allocates fresh virtual memory pages, copies code segments, and jumps straight
          to the entry offset.

7.The User Interface: The Shell.
        Once Ring 3 and storage work, the kernel's core initialization is complete.
        • The Init Process: The kernel spawns a single, standalone mini-shell as
          Process ID 1.
        • The Interface: A pure command-line environment communicating directly over
          serial or a raw frame-buffer terminal. No windows. No bloat. Just the metal.
